AN ACT relating to anatomical gifts; authorizing a procurement organization to
transport or arrange for the transportation of the body or part of a
deceased donor under certain circumstances; authorizing a coroner to
require a procurement organization to provide notice of such
transportation; and providing other matters properly relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 The Revised Uniform Anatomical Gift Act establishes the rights of donors and other
2 persons to affirmatively make anatomical gifts of human bodies and parts for the purpose of
3 transplantation, therapy, research or education. (NRS 451.500-451.598) The Uniform Act also
4 sets forth the rights and duties of organizations that procure anatomical gifts. (NRS 451.579)
5 This bill authorizes a procurement organization to transport, or arrange for the transportation
6 of, the body or part of a deceased donor [as necessary to facilitate an anatomical gift.] if
7 medical equipment is necessary to ensure the medical suitability of the body or part.
8 This bill also authorizes a coroner to require a procurement organization to notify the
9 coroner if the procurement organization provides or arranges for such transportation
10 within the jurisdiction of the coroner.
THE PEOPLE OF THE STATE OF NEVADA, REPRESENTED IN
SENATE AND ASSEMBLY, DO ENACT AS FOLLOWS:
1 Section 1. NRS 451.579 is hereby amended to read as follows:
2 451.579 1. When a hospital refers a natural person at or near death to a
3 procurement organization, the organization shall make a reasonable search of the
4 records of any donor registry that it knows exists for the geographical area in which
5 the natural person resides to ascertain whether the natural person has made an
6 anatomical gift.
7 2. When a hospital refers a natural person at or near death to a procurement
8 organization, the organization may conduct any reasonable examination necessary
9 to ensure the medical suitability of a part that is or could be the subject of an
10 anatomical gift for transplantation, therapy, research or education from a donor or a
11 prospective donor. During the examination period, measures necessary to ensure

